Green Men! 🌿 Made and modeled by me and A.J. 

Inspired by 'Jack in the Green' festivals in England and the old 'Green Man' decorative architectural ornaments on churches. 

The earliest known account of a Jack in the Green came from a description of a London May Day procession in 1770. The tradition died out in the early twentieth century. Later that century, various revivalist groups emerged, continuing the practice of 'Jack in the Green' May Day processions into today 💚🌿💚🌿💚

New Mexico dreams ✨ Modeling looks amongst the crumbling canyons at Bandelier National Monument - part of my Artist-In-Residency in the park. The canyons were formed by 'tuff', a type of rock made of volcanic ash ejected from vents. The tuff was erupted in a series of at least three ancient caldera eruptions in the local Jemez Mountains. The beautiful @vallescaldera site is near @bandeliernps - site of a massive explosion #bandeliernationalmonument #artistinresidence #falseface #vallescaldera #newmexico

Now on display in the Reinhardt University Faculty show: Birds, Bats, and Fox masks 🦇🪶🦊

This selection of my masks represents my interest in folkloric animal outfits. I often describe my work as a personal mythology filtered through ancient folklore. My masks, outfits, and sculptures use the materials of the old customs: ribbons, bells, flowers, horns, and vibrant paints. I am particularly fond of the rich, old traditions of the British Isles which only faintly echo into the American folk customs I grew up with in the Blue Ridge Mountains of Virginia. I see my work as an alternate reality, where the old festivals splintered into new forms with different fables. 

Let me know if you are interested in one of these masks, they are all for sale. 

Other talented artists in the show: @asc.graphicdesign @tamaradeanemce @rob.bunker.design @jschottstaedt @acdavis17

Helmet of Achelous, River Protector.  I made this piece inspired by Achelous, Greek God and protector of rivers. Achelous shapeshifted into a bull and battled Hercules (and lost). The horns symbolize the bull horns that Hercules snaped off during their wrestling match.  The small bottles hanging from the horns feature dirt and sand from different riverbeds and beaches.  This mask will be in the upcoming Summer Invitational show at Swan Coach House Gallery in Atlanta, curated by @jacob.okelley and @mariabruckmanart.  Details to follow in the coming weeks.  @swancoachhousegallery

I have eleven masks on display during the month of July at @turnipgreencreativereuse in Nashville, Tennessee...including three bats 🦇 This is the second time I've shown work with Turnip Green and I LOVE their mission of putting recycled, discarded materials into artist's hands.  Most of my work is made using found or second-hand materials...from the bells, beads, animal bones, and even the paper I use to construct the work. It was great to meet everyone at the opening event last weekend. Thanks to Jake @wellspaintings, Wallace  @shiny_wj, and the TG team for making this happen!  As I tell my University students, you don't need expensive art materials to make interesting work - use what is around you and apart of your daily life. Take something that is discarded and turn it into something magical 🪄♻️

Old Ned the Crow 🐦‍⬛ My (@jymdavis) tribute to an ancient Cornish (in Southwest England) custom known as the 'Blowing of May Horns'. During this folk custom, Ned the Crow dies and is reborn three times along a procession. The townspeople of Penzance and Newlyn create a very loud racket with 'May Horns' as well as pots and pans to cast out the devil of winter ❄️ It doesnt totally make sense to me either, which is why I love it! 

The 'Blowing of May Horns' is an ancient Cornish custom which vanished during the early years of the 20th century. These horns were often constructed from bark or branches of young trees in the local woodland. The custom is not dissimilar to the Hal-An-Tow in nearby Helston, where making as much noise as possible is greatly encouraged, to blow away the cold winter and usher in the long summer days.

This mask sold and now resides in Chicago 📍

Inspiration and historical context text via @reaphookandsickle (who participated in the May 2023 custom) ✌️

✨Work in progress✨ I'm creating a series of pieces inspired by mysterious 11,000 year old antler head dresses discovered in a northern English bog. I'm even taking an online mesolithic archaeology class about these 'frontlets' with University of York @uniofyork for inspiration (but of course my creations will be wildly interpretive and not at all historically accurate). Anyway, this is a glimpse into the finished 'paper sculpture' phase of my process....in this case I want a heavily distressed look for the head dress. I build up my masks with heavy papers and my own version of papier-mâché. Next I will seal the head dress with gesso and acrylic paint. If you're interested in more of how I make these things check out the 'frequently asked questions' on my website 🔗. Thanks for following along ✌️

I just finished this 'Protector' mask and shipped it to Hastings, England for a seaside art show entitled ART DEFENDS NATURE (opening August 26, Bat Cave Gallery at Rock-A-Nore). This mask includes trinkets and trash, collected during my recent Hastings / South England road trip. The objects included: bottled 'spoiled' beach & soil samples, discarded items like cork and keys, capiz and other shells, bells, rags, wood and glass beads, and (appropriately) an old paint brush. I'm donating 100% of sale profits to @xrhastingsstleonards, the sponsor of the show. 

The ART DEFENDS NATURE show asks the question, 'how can artists respond to the madness of the climate crisis? Not only to protest but to really see and truly celebrate the mystery and beauty that surrounds us. Can art help to change our relationship and connection to the natural world?' 

In my concept (based on a dream), the mask is for a protector figure who absorbs the detritus and debris that humans carelessly toss out. The piece symbolizes the burden of materialistic excess, which ultimately results in the despoiling of the natural world 🌎 Happy to be apart of this important art show 🙏✨
